{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Microorganisms that can utilise halogenated compounds as growth substrates produce enzymes that cleave carbon-halogen bonds and are commonly called dehalogenases. The hydrolytic dehalogenases catalyse a nucleophilic displacement reaction, with water as the sole co-substrate [[cite:PUB00000125]]. They are divided into haloalkane dehalogenases and haloacid dehalogenases (HAD). HADs belong to a large superfamily of hydrolases with diverse substrate specificity, which also includes epoxide hydrolases, phosphoglycolate phosphatases, histidinol phosphate phosphatases, nitrophenyl phosphatases and numerous other proteins [[cite:PUB00003337]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false} {"text" "<p>This entry represents the pyrophosphatase PpaX subfamily of the HAD superfamily. These enzymes hydrolyse pyrophosphate formed during P-Ser-HPr dephosphorylation by HPrK/P [[cite:PUB00054962]]. They may play a role in controlling the intracellular pyrophosphate pool.</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036412", "name" "HAD-like superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"} {"accession" "IPR023214", "name" "HAD superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"hamap" {"MF_01250" "Pyrophosphatase PpaX [ppaX]"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Pyrophosphatase PpaX", "short" "Pyrophosphatase_Ppax"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 0, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 228, "taxa" 805, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 816, "sets" 0, "proteins" 816, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 596}, "pathways" 2}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"ec" {"displayName" "ENZYME", "description" "ENZYME is a repository of information relative to the nomenclature of enzymes. It is primarily based on the recommendations of the Nomenclature Committee of the In